This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a distributed optimization algorithm for solving empirical risk minimization problems, which is a common task in machine learning. It may also belong to the distributed computing (cs.DC) sub-category as the algorithm is designed for distributed settings. Additionally, the paper involves numerical analysis (cs.NA) as it discusses the use of quadratic approximations and Hessian matrices. The paper may also be relevant to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category as it involves solving subproblems efficiently in a distributed manner. Finally, the paper may be relevant to the multi-agent systems (cs.MA) sub-category as it involves coordination among multiple agents in a distributed setting.
